cardiac parasympathetic regulation125. These fatty acids are integral to cell membrane structure, impacting fluidity and neurotransmitter function, and are noted for their anti-inflammatory properties6. Dose-Dependent Effects Evidence suggests a dose-dependent relationship where moderate intake (~500-700 mg/day of EPA and DHA) improves vagal tone, while higher doses (above 1000 mg/day) could lead to excessive vagal stimulation and increased risk of bradycardia-dependent arrhythmias such as atrial fibrillation14. High-dose omega-3 interventions have been linked to an increased risk of arrhythmias, which is an important consideration for susceptible individuals146. Comparison with Plant-Based Omega-3s Compared to marine sources, plant-based omega-3s like alpha-linolenic acid (ALA) have a less pronounced effect on vagal tone due to the limited conversion of ALA to EPA and DHA in humans6. Marine omega-3s consistently demonstrate stronger effects on heart function and vagal modulation than plant sources6910. Broader Dietary Patterns The Mediterranean diet, which is rich in fish and other beneficial nutrients, may support vagal tone through omega-3 intake and gut health improvement, suggesting a synergistic approach to enhancing vagal health61011. This aligns with evidence that whole dietary patterns, rather than isolated fatty acids, may offer broader cardiovascular and nervous system benefits. Lack of Direct Comparative Studies Currently, there is a lack of direct comparative studies explicitly ranking different omega-3 sources for their effects on vagus nerve health. Most research highlights marine omega-3s as the most effective in enhancing HRV and vagal tone, reinforced by their higher content of bioactive DHA and EPA610. Overall, marine omega-3s, whether from dietary fish or supplements, provide significant benefits for vagus nerve health, with some studies recommending a focus on dietary patterns to optimize these effects. How do omega-3 supplements compare to natu